value.value: A neoplasm that is non-capsulated.
A neoplasm that is confined to a specific site without evidence of spread to other anatomic sites.
A radiologic finding indicating the presence of a metastatic tumor in the bone(s) without associated bone destruction.

A neoplasm that arises from the mediastinum and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential. Representative examples include lipoma, leiomyoma, and schwannoma.
A term that refers to the categorization of malignant neoplasm by histologic grade.
A neoplasm whose histologic characteristics are intermediate between poorly differentiated and well differentiated.

A neoplasm that arises from the heart and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential. Representative examples include atrial myxoma, cardiac lipoma, and cardiac fibroma.
A neoplasm whose histologic characteristics have regressed and are more similar to stem cells.
A neoplasm that has minimal to no differentiating features.
A malignant neoplasm with morphological features reminiscent of the tissue from which it arose.

A non-encapsulated, well defined pulmonary blastoma, composed of irregular tubular structures.  It affects mostly middle-aged adults and it is rare in children.  The prognosis is better compared to the biphasic pulmonary blastoma.
A pulmonary blastoma composed of a mixture of irregular tubular structures and mesenchymal elements.

label.value: Acute Myeloid Leukemia with a Variant RARA Rearrangement

value.value: A term referring to acute myeloid leukemias which show variant translocations involving the RARA gene.  The variant fusion partners include NUMA1, ZBTB16, STAT5B, and NPM1.  These leukemias often have the morphologic features of acute promyelocytic leukemia.

label.value: Acute Myeloid Leukemia with t(11;17)(q23;q21); ZBTB16-RARA

value.value: Acute myeloid leukemia with the variant RARA t(11;17)(q23;q21) and the expression of ZBTB16-RARA fusion protein.  It lacks differentiation response to retinoids treatment.

label.value: Acute Myeloid Leukemia with t(5;17)(q35;q21); NPM1-RARA

value.value: Acute myeloid leukemia with the variant RARA t(5;17)(q35;q21) and the expression of NPM1-RARA fusion protein.

label.value: Acute Myeloid Leukemia with t(11;17)(q13;q21); NUMA1-RARA

value.value: Acute myeloid leukemia with the variant RARA t(11;17)(q13;q21) and the expression of NUMA1-RARA fusion protein.
A lipoma that arises from the spermatic cord.
A chronic myelomonocytic leukemia characterized by a peripheral blood eosinophil count of equal or greater than 1.5x10E9/L, and absence of PDGFRA or PDGFRB gene abnormalities.
A chronic myelomonocytic leukemia characterized by the presence of less than 10 percent blasts in the bone marrow and less than 5 percent blasts in the peripheral blood.

A chronic myelomonocytic leukemia characterized by the presence of 10-19 percent blasts in the bone marrow and 5-19 percent blasts in the peripheral blood or by the presence of Auer rods regardless of the blasts count.
Accumulation of hemorrhagic fluid in the peritoneal cavity.
Narrowing of the vaginal lumen.
Blockage of the lumen of the superior vena cava.
An infection that is caused by Orbivirus.
An acute inflammatory disorder of the colon secondary to infection with any species of the bacterial genus Clostridium. Symptoms include acute diarrhea, abdominal pain, and myalgia.

label.value: Posteroinferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of an injury in leads corresponding to the anatomic region of the posteroinferior wall of the heart.
An infectious process that affects the teeth and/or the periodontal tissues.

A neoplasm that arises from the cervix and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential. Representative examples include squamous papilloma, endocervical polyp, and rhabdomyoma.
An infection that affects the gastrointestinal system and the abdomen.
Polyneuropathy that is persistent or long-standing in nature.
A laboratory test result indicating other than normal parameters after a phenolsulfonphthaliein test.

label.value: Apical Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of an injury in leads corresponding to the anatomic region of the apex of the heart.

label.value: Metastatic Peripheral Primitive Neuroectodermal Tumor of Bone

value.value: A small round cell tumor of the bone with neural differentiation that has spread from its original site of growth to another anatomic site.

A rare histiocytic disorder of unknown etiology, characterized by distention of the lymph node sinuses and sinusoidal histiocytic infiltration. The histiocytes characteristically contain ingested lymphocytes and are S100 and CD68 positive, and CD1a negative. Patients present with cervical lymphadenopathy, fever, leukocytosis, and hypergammaglobulinemia. It can affect extranodal sites, including skin, bones, and the respiratory tract. It occurs in isolation or may be associated with autoimmune disorders or malignancies. Mutations in NRAS, KRAS, MAP2K1, and ARAF genes have been identified in affected tissues, suggesting a clonal origin in some cases. It is a self-limited disorder, although some patients may have a poor prognosis.

A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the male or female reproductive system.  Representative examples include prostate carcinoma, penile carcinoma, testicular seminoma, testicular embryonal carcinoma, endometrial carcinoma, cervical carcinoma, ovarian carcinoma, and uterine corpus leiomyosarcoma.
A carcinoma that arises from the junction, or adjacent to the junction, of the right and left hepatic ducts.
Anemia characterized by the production of ringed sideroblasts instead of healthy red blood cells.
A glomus tumor arising in the finger and usually associated with pain.

A neoplasm that arises from the uterine corpus and is characterized by the absence of atypical or malignant cytological and architectural features, and absence of invasive features or metastatic potential. Representative examples include leiomyoma, adenomyoma, endometrial stromal nodule, and endometrial polyp.

label.value: Diffuse Large B-Cell Lymphoma Germinal Center B-Cell Type

value.value: A biologic subset of diffuse large B-cell lymphomas with a unique molecular signature or expression profile.  It represents approximately 50% of diffuse large B-cell lymphomas, and is characterized by the expression of CD10, BCL-6, A-myb, and LMO2 genes, BCL-2 translocation, and c-REL amplification.  Morphologically, the vast majority of these lymphomas are centroblastic and a small minority are immunoblastic (ratio20:1).  Patients with this type of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma have a more favorable outcome, with a 5-year survival rate of 60% and a median survival of 10 years.
